{{Infobox Mars crater | name = Hussey Crater | image = Wikihusseydunes.jpg | caption = Hussey Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]). Dark dots are dunes. | coordinates = {{coord|53.8|S|126.7|W|globe:mars_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | discoverer = [[Mariner 4]] | diameter = 99 km | eponym = [[William Hussey (astronomer)|William Hussey]] }}'''Hussey Crater''' is an impact crater in the [[Phaethontis quadrangle]] on Mars at 53.8° S and 126.7° W. and is 99.0&nbsp;km in diameter. Its name was approved in 1973, and it was named after [[William Hussey (astronomer)]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature {{!}} Hussey|url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/2591|website=usgs.gov|publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]]|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>
The crater and the small vicinity was first imaged by [[Mariner 4]] in 1965 as its 17th image.
Nearby notable craters include [[Brashear (Martian crater)|Brashear]] to the east, that crater being in the [[Thaumasia quadrangle]], [[Dokuchaev (crater)|Dokuchaev]] to the south and [[Clark (Martian crater)|Clark]] not far to the west-southwest. Northwest and further north of Hussey are a series of rifts known as [[Icaria Fossae]].
Dunes are visible in the northern part of the crater floor. Also gullies are dominant in parts of its crater rims.
==Images== Pictures below show the dunes from a wide view and then eventually show greatly enlarged view with HiRISE. <gallery class="center" widths="190px" heights="180px" > Wikihussey.jpg|Dune field in Hussey Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter). Note: this is an enlargement of previous image. WikihusseyESP 039079 1270.jpg|Dunes in Hussey Crater, as seen by HiRISE. Note: this is an enlargement of the previous second image depicting its dunes </gallery>
