{{Infobox book | name = Meltdown | image = | image-size = | border = | alt = Cover of Meltdown (Clearfield and Tilcsik book), 2018 U.S. hardcover edition; scorched electrical socket over yellow background | caption = U.S. hardcover edition | author = Chris Clearfield, András Tilcsik | cover_artist = Christopher King | country = United States | language = English | subject =[[Failure]], [[System|Systems]], [[Sociology]] | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[Penguin Press]], [[Atlantic Books]], [[Penguin Random House|Penguin Random House Canada]] | pub_date = March 20, 2018 | media_type = Hardcover, paperback, audiobook | pages = 304 pg. | isbn = 9780735222632 | dewey= 158.1 | congress= HM701 .C54 2018 | oclc= 993419323 }} '''''Meltdown: Why Our Systems Fail and What We Can Do About It''''' is a [[non-fiction]] book by Chris Clearfield and András Tilcsik, published in March 2018 by [[Penguin Press]]. It explores how complexity causes failure in modern systems and how individuals, organizations, and societies can prevent or mitigate the resulting meltdowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/549596/meltdown-by-chris-clearfield-and-andras-tilcsik/9780735222632/|title=Meltdown by Chris Clearfield, András Tilcsik {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|website=PenguinRandomhouse.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref> The [[Financial Times|''Financial Times'']] selected ''Meltdown'' as one of the books of year in 2018.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4366fc54-ee04-11e8-89c8-d36339d835c0|title=Best books of 2018: Business|last=Hill|first=Andrew|date=November 23, 2018|website=Financial Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
== Background == The book is the result of a collaboration between Chris Clearfield, a former derivatives trader, and András Tilcsik, a professor at the [[University of Toronto]]'s [[Rotman School of Management]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/meltdown-review-flirting-with-disaster-1522708270|title=‘Meltdown’ Review: Flirting With Disaster|last=Shaywitz|first=David A.|date=April 2, 2018|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref> Clearfield and Tilcsik took top honors in the 2015 competition for [[Bracken Bower Prize|''The Financial Times'' and McKinsey Bracken Bower Prize]] with their proposal for a book about how to understand systemic risk and prevent catastrophic failures in business and beyond. The following year, they signed with [[Penguin Press]] to publish ''Meltdown''.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eefab158-0330-11e6-af1d-c47326021344|title=FT/McKinsey contest helps business book hopefuls land deals|last=Hill|first=Andrew|date=2016-04-24|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mckinsey.com/about-us/new-at-mckinsey-blog/blazing-a-trail-from-prize-to-publication|title=Blazing a trail from prize to publication|website=McKinsey & Company|language=en|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>
== Synopsis == The first three chapters of the book extend [[Charles Perrow]]’s ''[[Normal Accidents|normal accident theory]]''—originally developed in the 1980s—to recent trends, such as the rise of [[social media]], the increasing reliance of organizations on computer-based systems, and the growing [[complexity]] of modern financial, transportation, and communication systems. The authors warn that companies, governments, and even individuals have become dangerously reliant on [[Complex system|complex]], [[Tight coupling|tightly coupled]] systems and are ignoring simple fixes that could avert both [[Accident|accidents]] and intentional [[wrongdoing]].{{sfn|Clearfield|Tilcsik|2018|pp=1–78}}
Each of the remaining chapters focuses on a different set of solutions: designing more transparent and [[loosely coupled]] systems (Chapter 4); using structured [[Decision tool|decision tools]] (Chapter 5); learning from [[Near miss (safety)|near misses]] and other warning signs (Chapter 6); encouraging [[dissent]] and [[skepticism]] (Chapter 7); building [[Diversity (politics)|diverse]] teams (Chapter 8); learning from [[The Stranger (sociology)|outsiders]] (Chapter 9); and preparing for and [[Crisis management|managing crises]] more effectively (Chapter 10).{{sfn|Clearfield|Tilcsik|2018|pp=81–239}}
In the [[epilogue]], the authors state that humanity is in “the [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of meltdowns”: though modern systems give us tremendous capabilities, they also make us vulnerable to unexpected system failures. Clearfield and Tilcsik, however, express optimism about the future and argue that the solutions are within reach. At the same time, they caution that putting the necessary solutions into practice is difficult because doing so often goes against our natural [[Instinct|instincts]] and violates persistent organizational and cultural [[Social norm|norms]].{{sfn|Clearfield|Tilcsik|2018|pp=241–245}}
== Style == The book combines analyses of [[Case study|case studies]] with summaries of [[social science]] research, drawing on academic studies, accident reports, and original interviews. The case studies include, for example, a failed social media campaign at [[Starbucks]], a [[Thanksgiving dinner]] gone awry, the [[Three Mile Island accident|Three Mile Island nuclear accident]], the [[Flint water crisis]], [[Nasdaq, Inc.|Nasdaq]]’s botched handling of the [[Facebook]] [[Initial public offering|IPO]], the accidents of the space shuttles [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|''Challenger'']] and [[Space Shuttle Columbia disaster|''Columbia'']], the electronic trading meltdown of [[Knight Capital Group|Knight Capital]], the crashes of flights [[ValuJet Flight 592|ValuJet 592]] and [[Air France Flight 447|Air France 447]], and the [[June 2009 Washington Metro train collision]].The academic research covered in the book comes from [[sociology]], [[psychology]], [[Behavioral economics|behavioural economics]], [[organizational theory]], and [[neuroscience]], including studies by [[Charles Perrow]], [[Diane Vaughan]], [[Karl E. Weick|Karl Weick]], [[Amy Edmondson]], [[Dacher Keltner]], [[Gary A. Klein|Gary Klein]], [[Gregory Berns]], [[Daniel Kahneman]], and [[Georg Simmel]], among others.
== Reception == The [[Financial Times|''Financial Times'']] called ''Meltdown'' "an exciting and insightful analysis of why things go wrong and how to avoid catastrophe" and selected it as one of the books of 2018.<ref name=":4" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5ab89d6e-2135-11e8-a895-1ba1f72c2c11|title=FT business books of the month: March edition|last=Hill|first=Andrew|date=March 9, 2018|work=The Financial Times|access-date=August 7, 2018|last2=Conboye|first2=Janina|pmc=|ssrn=|last3=Jacobs|first3=Emma}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/dc6bcae6-7a6f-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=Summer books of 2018: Business|last=Hill|first=Andrew|date=June 29, 2018|work=The Financial Times|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref> David A. Shaywitz, reviewing the book in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', concluded that "''Meltdown'' effectively conveys why addressing systemic failures is both difficult and essential: difficult because it’s so much more comfortable to rely on gut instinct and trust familiar colleagues than to insist on structured approaches and solicit the views of others; essential because we are moving into the danger zone and need all the help we can get." Shaywitz called the book’s examples "illuminating" and noted that "where ''Meltdown'' really hits its stride is in taking on the factors that promote groupthink and discourage dissent."<ref name=":3" />
Leigh Buchanan, editor-at-large at [[Inc. (magazine)|''Inc.'' magazine]], named ''Meltdown'' as one of the "eight books you need to read in 2018" and described it as "admirably evidence-based."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.inc.com/leigh-buchanan/2018-books-preview.html|title=Bill Gates, Warren Buffett, and Mark Cuban Consume 50 Books a Year (More or Less). Here Are 8 You Need to Read in 2018|last=Buchanan|first=Leigh|date=|work=Inc.|access-date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> Writing for [[Forbes.com]], Brook Manville called ''Meltdown'' "a thought-provoking new book" and wrote that the authors "colorfully explain why your job, like everyone else’s in today’s global economy, is becoming part of bigger networks of co-dependent systems, laden with unforeseeable risks and unimaginable outcomes."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brookmanville/2018/07/08/how-to-get-ready-for-big-system-failure-headed-your-way/#7a1ca80f528e|title=How To Get Ready For Big System Failure Headed Your Way|last=Manville|first=Brook|date=|work=Forbes.com|access-date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> [[Kirkus Reviews]] described ''Meltdown'' as "a useful, thought-provoking book" and "a cautionary study in how complex systems can easily go awry".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/chris-clearfield/meltdown-systems/|title=Review: MELTDOWN Why Our Systems Fail and What We Can Do About It|last=|first=|date=December 24, 2017|website=Kirkus Reviews|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> ''[[CBS This Morning]]'' co-host [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] called the book "really interesting"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/radio-atlantic-is-the-presidency-broken/559061/|title=Radio Atlantic: Is the Presidency Broken?|last=|first=|date=|website=The Atlantic|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> and "a great new book."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/cbsthismorning/simplicity-and-transparency-keys-to-preventing-a-meltdown|title=Simplicity and Transparency: Keys to Preventing a Meltdown|last=Dickerson|first=John|date=|website=Soundcloud - CBS This Morning Podcast|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> In a book review for ''[[Strategy+Business]]'', Theodore Kinni wrote that "''Meltdown'' is something of a rarity: an enlightening and entertaining business book. It synthesizes the work of experts in high-risk systems . . . and builds upon it in an accessible and practical way."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.strategy-business.com/article/How-to-Become-a-Master-of-Disaster?gko=a3028|title=How to Become a Master of Disaster|last=Theodore|first=Kinni|date=June 4, 2018|work=Strategy+Business|access-date=August 7, 2018}}</ref>
