'''Vitaly Napadow''' is a Ukrainian-born American neuroscientist and acupuncturist. He is associate professor at [[Harvard Medical School]] and the [[Martinos Center for Biomedical Imaging]]. He is also the director of the Center for Integrative Pain NeuroImaging and the co-president of the Society for Acupuncture Research.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scholar.harvard.edu/napadow/vitaly |title=Vitaly Napadow, PhD LicAc |website=scholar.harvard.edu |language=en |access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref> He is known for researching [[acupuncture]] and its effects on the brain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/02/well/live/acupuncture-can-ease-wrist-pain-of-carpal-tunnel-syndrome.html |title=Acupuncture Can Ease Wrist Pain of Carpal Tunnel Syndrome |last=Bakalar |first=Nicholas |date=2017-03-02 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html |title=A Chinese Art, In the Context Of the West |last=Alderman |first=Lesley |date=2010-05-08 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref> He has also researched the effects of [[nausea]] on brain activation,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/researchers-look-for-effective-treatments-for-a-common-problem-nausea/2013/11/18/58c5c630-4b06-11e3-9890-a1e0997fb0c0_story.html |title=Researchers look for effective treatments for a common problem: Nausea |last=Powell |first=Kendall |date=2013-11-18 |website=Washington Post |access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref> and differences in resting state brain connectivity associated with the intensity of spontaneous [[fibromyalgia]] pain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Health_News/2010/07/31/Resting-brain-linked-to-fibromyalgia-pain/UPI-61971280634527/ |title=Resting brain linked to fibromyalgia pain |date=2010-07-31 |website=UPI |language=en |access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>
==Biography== Napadow received his [[master's degree]] in acupuncture from the New England School of Acupuncture in 2002 and his Ph.D. from the [[Harvard–MIT Program of Health Sciences and Technology]] in 2001. He joined the faculty of Harvard Medical School in 2004 as an instructor in [[radiology]], where he became an assistant professor of anesthesiology in 2010 and an associate professor of radiology in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scholar.harvard.edu/files/napadow/files/cv_harvard_napadow_06_2017.pdf |title=Vitaly Napadow CV}}</ref>
